\[ \begin{aligned} p(x_1, \ldots, x_n) &amp;= \prod_{i=1}^n p(x_i \mid \mathrm{pa}(x_i)) \\ &amp;= p(x_n \mid x_1, \ldots, x_{n-1}) \ldots p(x_2 \mid x_1) p(x_1) \end{aligned} \] <p>\(\mathrm{pa}(x_i)\) denotes the set of parents of \(x_i\)</p> <p>We call this directed factorization property. A graph describes a set of conditional independence properties.</p> <p></p> <p>the set of distributions \(\mathcal{DF}\) will include any distributions that have additional independence properties beyond those described by the graph.</p> <p>The more independence properties a distributions has, the harder it get filtered out.</p> Tip <p></p> <p>For this MkDocs site, use Graphviz/DOT for graphical models. It supports reusable node and edge defaults and plate-style clusters.</p> <p>Bayesian network</p> <pre><code>digraph G {
  rankdir=LR;

  node [shape=circle, style=filled, fillcolor=white];

  Cloudy -&gt; Sprinkler;
  Cloudy -&gt; Rain;
  Sprinkler -&gt; WetGrass;
  Rain -&gt; WetGrass;
}</code></pre> <p>This represents the factorization</p> \[ p(C, S, R, W) = p(C)p(S \mid C)p(R \mid C)p(W \mid S, R). \] <p>The absence of links in the graph that conveys interesting information about the properties of the class of distributions that the graph represents.</p> 8.3 \[p(a=1, b=1 \mid c=1) = 0.1846154\] \[p(a=1 \mid c=1) = 0.3076923\] \[p(b=1 \mid c=1) = 0.6\]
